</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Overlap of breast tissue is a frequent consequence of the necessary positioning and compression of the three-dimensional breast to obtain two-dimensional mammograms. The mammary glands contain fewer anatomically fixed landmarks than solid organs do; thus, variability in positioning can have an even greater effect on mammography than it has on other imaging examinations. Most often, areas of overlapping fibroglandular tissue, also known as summation shadows, are seen on only one of the two standard mammographic views. While striving to detect breast cancer as early as possible, radiologists must learn to visually compensate for apparent abnormalities in the breast that are produced by such tissue overlap. Mammographic interpretation in this setting is made even more challenging by the fact that the only manifestation of breast cancer might be a subtle change on a single mammographic view. Breast cancer might be obscured on one of the two standard views because of the density of surrounding breast tissue, mammographic technique, lesion size or location within the breast, histopathologic characteristics of the tumor, or lack of effect by the tumor on the appearance of surrounding tissues. To heighten awareness of the factors that can lead to either unnecessary recalls or failure to identify breast cancer, cases are reviewed in which false-positive findings and breast cancers were visible on only one mammographic view. Strategies for interpreting screening mammograms and determining which findings merit diagnostic evaluation are outlined so as to help minimize false-positive findings and aid in cancer detection.</div><div role="paragraph">©RSNA, 2014</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.344130066">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.344130066">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig1a.jpeg" height="1028" width="1099" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Origin of summation artifacts. <b>(a)</b> Schematic of noncompressed breast sections shows several discrete fibroglandular densities (white ovoids) in planes at varying depths along the z-axis (black arrows) but with similar two-dimensional (2D) coordinates along the x- and y-axes (white arrows). <b>(b)</b> Schematic of the compressed breast shows how compression can result in overlap of these areas of fibroglandular tissue, creating the appearance of a 3D pseudolesion (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig1b.jpeg" height="1028" width="1352" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Origin of summation artifacts. <b>(a)</b> Schematic of noncompressed breast sections shows several discrete fibroglandular densities (white ovoids) in planes at varying depths along the z-axis (black arrows) but with similar two-dimensional (2D) coordinates along the x- and y-axes (white arrows). <b>(b)</b> Schematic of the compressed breast shows how compression can result in overlap of these areas of fibroglandular tissue, creating the appearance of a 3D pseudolesion (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig2a.jpeg" height="1046" width="451" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Spurious asymmetry due to overlap of tissue in a dense breast. <b>(a)</b> CC view obtained in 2012 shows an asymmetry (arrow) that is not seen either on <b>b</b>, the MLO view from the same mammographic examination, or on <b>c</b>, the CC view from screening in 2011. Comparison with a CC view from an older mammogram (not shown) showed a similar appearance of the breast tissue.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig2b.jpeg" height="1046" width="373" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Spurious asymmetry due to overlap of tissue in a dense breast. <b>(a)</b> CC view obtained in 2012 shows an asymmetry (arrow) that is not seen either on <b>b</b>, the MLO view from the same mammographic examination, or on <b>c</b>, the CC view from screening in 2011. Comparison with a CC view from an older mammogram (not shown) showed a similar appearance of the breast tissue.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig2c.jpeg" height="1046" width="476" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span> Spurious asymmetry due to overlap of tissue in a dense breast. <b>(a)</b> CC view obtained in 2012 shows an asymmetry (arrow) that is not seen either on <b>b</b>, the MLO view from the same mammographic examination, or on <b>c</b>, the CC view from screening in 2011. Comparison with a CC view from an older mammogram (not shown) showed a similar appearance of the breast tissue.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig3a.jpeg" height="816" width="650" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Spurious asymmetry due to overlap of tissue in a breast with predominant fat density. <b>(a)</b> MLO view depicts several areas of fibroglandular tissue at varying depths within the breast (oval). <b>(b)</b> Orthogonal CC view shows an asymmetry or summation artifact produced by the overlapping areas of fibroglandular tissue (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig3b.jpeg" height="816" width="675" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Spurious asymmetry due to overlap of tissue in a breast with predominant fat density. <b>(a)</b> MLO view depicts several areas of fibroglandular tissue at varying depths within the breast (oval). <b>(b)</b> Orthogonal CC view shows an asymmetry or summation artifact produced by the overlapping areas of fibroglandular tissue (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig4a.jpeg" height="685" width="501" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> <b>(a)</b> Schematic shows how disparity in thickness between the anterior and posterior parts of the breast leads to nonuniform compression due to centering of the compressive force over the thicker posterior portion (thick arrow) while the less thick anterior portion (thin arrows) is undercompressed. One of our technologists has dubbed such tapering of the anterior part of the breast an “aardvark” configuration. <b>(b)</b> Routine CC view shows an apparent architectural distortion (arrows) due to undercompression of the anterior part of the breast. <b>(c)</b> CC view obtained with anterior spot compression shows no persistent abnormality. Breast US (not shown) likewise depicted no abnormality corresponding to the asymmetry in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig4b.jpeg" height="1059" width="413" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> <b>(a)</b> Schematic shows how disparity in thickness between the anterior and posterior parts of the breast leads to nonuniform compression due to centering of the compressive force over the thicker posterior portion (thick arrow) while the less thick anterior portion (thin arrows) is undercompressed. One of our technologists has dubbed such tapering of the anterior part of the breast an “aardvark” configuration. <b>(b)</b> Routine CC view shows an apparent architectural distortion (arrows) due to undercompression of the anterior part of the breast. <b>(c)</b> CC view obtained with anterior spot compression shows no persistent abnormality. Breast US (not shown) likewise depicted no abnormality corresponding to the asymmetry in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig4c.jpeg" height="1059" width="636" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span> <b>(a)</b> Schematic shows how disparity in thickness between the anterior and posterior parts of the breast leads to nonuniform compression due to centering of the compressive force over the thicker posterior portion (thick arrow) while the less thick anterior portion (thin arrows) is undercompressed. One of our technologists has dubbed such tapering of the anterior part of the breast an “aardvark” configuration. <b>(b)</b> Routine CC view shows an apparent architectural distortion (arrows) due to undercompression of the anterior part of the breast. <b>(c)</b> CC view obtained with anterior spot compression shows no persistent abnormality. Breast US (not shown) likewise depicted no abnormality corresponding to the asymmetry in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig5a.jpeg" height="962" width="470" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Weight loss results in a one-view finding in the medial part of the breast at routine screening in a patient who had lost 60 pounds since her previous mammographic examination. <b>(a, b)</b> Comparison of the 2009 CC view <b>(a)</b> with the 2011 CC view <b>(b)</b> shows an apparent asymmetry in <b>b</b> (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Subsequent spot compression CC view shows no asymmetry.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig5b.jpeg" height="962" width="493" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Weight loss results in a one-view finding in the medial part of the breast at routine screening in a patient who had lost 60 pounds since her previous mammographic examination. <b>(a, b)</b> Comparison of the 2009 CC view <b>(a)</b> with the 2011 CC view <b>(b)</b> shows an apparent asymmetry in <b>b</b> (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Subsequent spot compression CC view shows no asymmetry.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig5c.jpeg" height="962" width="595" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> Weight loss results in a one-view finding in the medial part of the breast at routine screening in a patient who had lost 60 pounds since her previous mammographic examination. <b>(a, b)</b> Comparison of the 2009 CC view <b>(a)</b> with the 2011 CC view <b>(b)</b> shows an apparent asymmetry in <b>b</b> (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Subsequent spot compression CC view shows no asymmetry.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig6a.jpeg" height="929" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Small one-view cancer seen at screening. <b>(a)</b> CC view shows an asymmetry laterally (arrow). <b>(b)</b> MLO view shows scattered areas of fibroglandular tissue, which obscure the lesion. On the basis of rolled CC views (not shown), the lesion was thought to be in the superior part of the breast. <b>(c)</b> Spot compression MLO view demonstrates the lesion (arrow), which proved to be a small invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig6b.jpeg" height="830" width="630" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Small one-view cancer seen at screening. <b>(a)</b> CC view shows an asymmetry laterally (arrow). <b>(b)</b> MLO view shows scattered areas of fibroglandular tissue, which obscure the lesion. On the basis of rolled CC views (not shown), the lesion was thought to be in the superior part of the breast. <b>(c)</b> Spot compression MLO view demonstrates the lesion (arrow), which proved to be a small invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig6c.jpeg" height="830" width="694" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> Small one-view cancer seen at screening. <b>(a)</b> CC view shows an asymmetry laterally (arrow). <b>(b)</b> MLO view shows scattered areas of fibroglandular tissue, which obscure the lesion. On the basis of rolled CC views (not shown), the lesion was thought to be in the superior part of the breast. <b>(c)</b> Spot compression MLO view demonstrates the lesion (arrow), which proved to be a small invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig7a.jpeg" height="963" width="520" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Comparison of initial and repeat MLO views illustrates the importance of adequate compression for demonstrating small malignancies within dense breast tissue. <b>(a)</b> Centering the compression paddle over the posterior portion of the breast in an effort to include sufficient pectoral muscle in the image area led to undercompression of the central part of the breast, with resultant obscuration of a small cancer. <b>(b)</b> Repeat MLO view obtained with the paddle centered over the central cone of fibroglandular tissue clearly depicts the cancer (arrow). The lesion was not seen on CC views.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig7b.jpeg" height="963" width="505" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Comparison of initial and repeat MLO views illustrates the importance of adequate compression for demonstrating small malignancies within dense breast tissue. <b>(a)</b> Centering the compression paddle over the posterior portion of the breast in an effort to include sufficient pectoral muscle in the image area led to undercompression of the central part of the breast, with resultant obscuration of a small cancer. <b>(b)</b> Repeat MLO view obtained with the paddle centered over the central cone of fibroglandular tissue clearly depicts the cancer (arrow). The lesion was not seen on CC views.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig8a.jpeg" height="985" width="413" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> <b>(a, b)</b> An asymmetry with associated architectural distortion in the central breast is visible on the CC view (arrows in <b>a</b>) but not on the MLO view <b>(b)</b>. The presence of distortion increased the likelihood that this abnormality was a malignant lesion, so although it was evident on only one view, it was considered to merit diagnostic evaluation. During the subsequent workup, the lesion could not be visualized on ML or spot MLO views (not shown). <b>(c, d)</b> Rolled CC views (<b>c</b> obtained with the superior part of the breast rolled laterally; <b>d</b> obtained with the superior part of the breast rolled medially) show persistence of the abnormality (arrows) without a substantial change in its location, a finding suggestive of a central location at the level of the nipple. Findings at breast US were negative. The results of a stereotactic needle biopsy showed invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig8b.jpeg" height="985" width="563" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> <b>(a, b)</b> An asymmetry with associated architectural distortion in the central breast is visible on the CC view (arrows in <b>a</b>) but not on the MLO view <b>(b)</b>. The presence of distortion increased the likelihood that this abnormality was a malignant lesion, so although it was evident on only one view, it was considered to merit diagnostic evaluation. During the subsequent workup, the lesion could not be visualized on ML or spot MLO views (not shown). <b>(c, d)</b> Rolled CC views (<b>c</b> obtained with the superior part of the breast rolled laterally; <b>d</b> obtained with the superior part of the breast rolled medially) show persistence of the abnormality (arrows) without a substantial change in its location, a finding suggestive of a central location at the level of the nipple. Findings at breast US were negative. The results of a stereotactic needle biopsy showed invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig8c.jpeg" height="985" width="423" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span> <b>(a, b)</b> An asymmetry with associated architectural distortion in the central breast is visible on the CC view (arrows in <b>a</b>) but not on the MLO view <b>(b)</b>. The presence of distortion increased the likelihood that this abnormality was a malignant lesion, so although it was evident on only one view, it was considered to merit diagnostic evaluation. During the subsequent workup, the lesion could not be visualized on ML or spot MLO views (not shown). <b>(c, d)</b> Rolled CC views (<b>c</b> obtained with the superior part of the breast rolled laterally; <b>d</b> obtained with the superior part of the breast rolled medially) show persistence of the abnormality (arrows) without a substantial change in its location, a finding suggestive of a central location at the level of the nipple. Findings at breast US were negative. The results of a stereotactic needle biopsy showed invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig8d.jpeg" height="985" width="426" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span> <b>(a, b)</b> An asymmetry with associated architectural distortion in the central breast is visible on the CC view (arrows in <b>a</b>) but not on the MLO view <b>(b)</b>. The presence of distortion increased the likelihood that this abnormality was a malignant lesion, so although it was evident on only one view, it was considered to merit diagnostic evaluation. During the subsequent workup, the lesion could not be visualized on ML or spot MLO views (not shown). <b>(c, d)</b> Rolled CC views (<b>c</b> obtained with the superior part of the breast rolled laterally; <b>d</b> obtained with the superior part of the breast rolled medially) show persistence of the abnormality (arrows) without a substantial change in its location, a finding suggestive of a central location at the level of the nipple. Findings at breast US were negative. The results of a stereotactic needle biopsy showed invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig9a.jpeg" height="873" width="489" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Invasive ductal cancers detected at routine breast screening in two patients. Because these lesions were in extremely posterior medial <b>(a, b)</b> and lateral <b>(c, d)</b> locations in the breast, they were seen on only one view at routine mammography. <b>(a)</b> Standard MLO view shows an asymmetry (arrow) in the posterior upper part of the breast overlying the pectoral muscle. <b>(b)</b> Diagnostic ML view obtained with spot compression shows the same abnormality (arrow). The lesion is more superiorly located on the ML spot compression view than on the MLO view, a finding suggestive of a location in the upper inner part of the breast. No abnormality was seen on the CC views. US-guided biopsy showed the lesion to be an invasive ductal cancer located high on the chest wall, in the upper inner quadrant. <b>(c)</b> MLO view shows an asymmetry (arrow) in the posterior superior part of the breast. The abnormality was not visible on the screening CC view (not shown). <b>(d)</b> Laterally exaggerated diagnostic CC view helps determine that the lesion (arrow) is located in the posterior-lateral breast. US-guided core needle biopsy showed invasive ductal cancer<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig9b.jpeg" height="873" width="566" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Invasive ductal cancers detected at routine breast screening in two patients. Because these lesions were in extremely posterior medial <b>(a, b)</b> and lateral <b>(c, d)</b> locations in the breast, they were seen on only one view at routine mammography. <b>(a)</b> Standard MLO view shows an asymmetry (arrow) in the posterior upper part of the breast overlying the pectoral muscle. <b>(b)</b> Diagnostic ML view obtained with spot compression shows the same abnormality (arrow). The lesion is more superiorly located on the ML spot compression view than on the MLO view, a finding suggestive of a location in the upper inner part of the breast. No abnormality was seen on the CC views. US-guided biopsy showed the lesion to be an invasive ductal cancer located high on the chest wall, in the upper inner quadrant. <b>(c)</b> MLO view shows an asymmetry (arrow) in the posterior superior part of the breast. The abnormality was not visible on the screening CC view (not shown). <b>(d)</b> Laterally exaggerated diagnostic CC view helps determine that the lesion (arrow) is located in the posterior-lateral breast. US-guided core needle biopsy showed invasive ductal cancer<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig9c.jpeg" height="873" width="409" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> Invasive ductal cancers detected at routine breast screening in two patients. Because these lesions were in extremely posterior medial <b>(a, b)</b> and lateral <b>(c, d)</b> locations in the breast, they were seen on only one view at routine mammography. <b>(a)</b> Standard MLO view shows an asymmetry (arrow) in the posterior upper part of the breast overlying the pectoral muscle. <b>(b)</b> Diagnostic ML view obtained with spot compression shows the same abnormality (arrow). The lesion is more superiorly located on the ML spot compression view than on the MLO view, a finding suggestive of a location in the upper inner part of the breast. No abnormality was seen on the CC views. US-guided biopsy showed the lesion to be an invasive ductal cancer located high on the chest wall, in the upper inner quadrant. <b>(c)</b> MLO view shows an asymmetry (arrow) in the posterior superior part of the breast. The abnormality was not visible on the screening CC view (not shown). <b>(d)</b> Laterally exaggerated diagnostic CC view helps determine that the lesion (arrow) is located in the posterior-lateral breast. US-guided core needle biopsy showed invasive ductal cancer<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig9d.jpeg" height="873" width="361" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span> Invasive ductal cancers detected at routine breast screening in two patients. Because these lesions were in extremely posterior medial <b>(a, b)</b> and lateral <b>(c, d)</b> locations in the breast, they were seen on only one view at routine mammography. <b>(a)</b> Standard MLO view shows an asymmetry (arrow) in the posterior upper part of the breast overlying the pectoral muscle. <b>(b)</b> Diagnostic ML view obtained with spot compression shows the same abnormality (arrow). The lesion is more superiorly located on the ML spot compression view than on the MLO view, a finding suggestive of a location in the upper inner part of the breast. No abnormality was seen on the CC views. US-guided biopsy showed the lesion to be an invasive ductal cancer located high on the chest wall, in the upper inner quadrant. <b>(c)</b> MLO view shows an asymmetry (arrow) in the posterior superior part of the breast. The abnormality was not visible on the screening CC view (not shown). <b>(d)</b> Laterally exaggerated diagnostic CC view helps determine that the lesion (arrow) is located in the posterior-lateral breast. US-guided core needle biopsy showed invasive ductal cancer<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig10.jpeg" height="923" width="1799" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span> Schematic shows the centimeter-wide peripheral layer of breast tissue in which a preponderance of breast malignancies are reported to be found—perhaps because this region accounts for more than 50% of the total breast tissue volume. (Adapted, with permission, from reference 17.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig11a.jpeg" height="865" width="348" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> <b>(a)</b> MLO view shows a subtle architectural distortion (arrow) in the posterior peripheral part of the fibroglandular tissue. <b>(b)</b> CC view fails to show the junction between the fibroglandular tissue and the retromammary fat, although the depth of the breast tissue on this CC view is within 1 cm of the depth on the MLO view and the mammogram thus would be considered technically adequate. <b>(c, d)</b> Spot compression MLO <b>(c)</b> and laterally exaggerated CC <b>(d)</b> views show persistence of the distortion (arrow). The lesion proved to be a small invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig11b.jpeg" height="865" width="386" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> <b>(a)</b> MLO view shows a subtle architectural distortion (arrow) in the posterior peripheral part of the fibroglandular tissue. <b>(b)</b> CC view fails to show the junction between the fibroglandular tissue and the retromammary fat, although the depth of the breast tissue on this CC view is within 1 cm of the depth on the MLO view and the mammogram thus would be considered technically adequate. <b>(c, d)</b> Spot compression MLO <b>(c)</b> and laterally exaggerated CC <b>(d)</b> views show persistence of the distortion (arrow). The lesion proved to be a small invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig11c.jpeg" height="865" width="549" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span> <b>(a)</b> MLO view shows a subtle architectural distortion (arrow) in the posterior peripheral part of the fibroglandular tissue. <b>(b)</b> CC view fails to show the junction between the fibroglandular tissue and the retromammary fat, although the depth of the breast tissue on this CC view is within 1 cm of the depth on the MLO view and the mammogram thus would be considered technically adequate. <b>(c, d)</b> Spot compression MLO <b>(c)</b> and laterally exaggerated CC <b>(d)</b> views show persistence of the distortion (arrow). The lesion proved to be a small invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig11d.jpeg" height="865" width="541" aria-labelledby="fig11d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span> <b>(a)</b> MLO view shows a subtle architectural distortion (arrow) in the posterior peripheral part of the fibroglandular tissue. <b>(b)</b> CC view fails to show the junction between the fibroglandular tissue and the retromammary fat, although the depth of the breast tissue on this CC view is within 1 cm of the depth on the MLO view and the mammogram thus would be considered technically adequate. <b>(c, d)</b> Spot compression MLO <b>(c)</b> and laterally exaggerated CC <b>(d)</b> views show persistence of the distortion (arrow). The lesion proved to be a small invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig12a.jpeg" height="847" width="457" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Small invasive ductal cancer. <b>(a, b)</b> Comparison of CC views obtained in 2012 <b>(a)</b> and 2010 <b>(b)</b> shows a one-view asymmetry (arrow in <b>a</b>) with questionable architectural distortion. <b>(c, d)</b> Comparison of MLO views acquired in 2012 <b>(c)</b> and 2010 <b>(d)</b> shows a stable appearance of the breast. <b>(e, f)</b> During the ensuing diagnostic evaluation, the technologist first obtained a spot compression view with the large square paddle <b>(e)</b>, which did not show the spiculated margins indicative of malignancy as clearly as did the compression view obtained with the small round paddle <b>(f)</b>, which focused more compressive force over the location of the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig12b.jpeg" height="847" width="445" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Small invasive ductal cancer. <b>(a, b)</b> Comparison of CC views obtained in 2012 <b>(a)</b> and 2010 <b>(b)</b> shows a one-view asymmetry (arrow in <b>a</b>) with questionable architectural distortion. <b>(c, d)</b> Comparison of MLO views acquired in 2012 <b>(c)</b> and 2010 <b>(d)</b> shows a stable appearance of the breast. <b>(e, f)</b> During the ensuing diagnostic evaluation, the technologist first obtained a spot compression view with the large square paddle <b>(e)</b>, which did not show the spiculated margins indicative of malignancy as clearly as did the compression view obtained with the small round paddle <b>(f)</b>, which focused more compressive force over the location of the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig12c.jpeg" height="847" width="453" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> Small invasive ductal cancer. <b>(a, b)</b> Comparison of CC views obtained in 2012 <b>(a)</b> and 2010 <b>(b)</b> shows a one-view asymmetry (arrow in <b>a</b>) with questionable architectural distortion. <b>(c, d)</b> Comparison of MLO views acquired in 2012 <b>(c)</b> and 2010 <b>(d)</b> shows a stable appearance of the breast. <b>(e, f)</b> During the ensuing diagnostic evaluation, the technologist first obtained a spot compression view with the large square paddle <b>(e)</b>, which did not show the spiculated margins indicative of malignancy as clearly as did the compression view obtained with the small round paddle <b>(f)</b>, which focused more compressive force over the location of the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig12d.jpeg" height="847" width="471" aria-labelledby="fig12d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span> Small invasive ductal cancer. <b>(a, b)</b> Comparison of CC views obtained in 2012 <b>(a)</b> and 2010 <b>(b)</b> shows a one-view asymmetry (arrow in <b>a</b>) with questionable architectural distortion. <b>(c, d)</b> Comparison of MLO views acquired in 2012 <b>(c)</b> and 2010 <b>(d)</b> shows a stable appearance of the breast. <b>(e, f)</b> During the ensuing diagnostic evaluation, the technologist first obtained a spot compression view with the large square paddle <b>(e)</b>, which did not show the spiculated margins indicative of malignancy as clearly as did the compression view obtained with the small round paddle <b>(f)</b>, which focused more compressive force over the location of the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig12e.jpeg" height="819" width="515" aria-labelledby="fig12e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12e</span> Small invasive ductal cancer. <b>(a, b)</b> Comparison of CC views obtained in 2012 <b>(a)</b> and 2010 <b>(b)</b> shows a one-view asymmetry (arrow in <b>a</b>) with questionable architectural distortion. <b>(c, d)</b> Comparison of MLO views acquired in 2012 <b>(c)</b> and 2010 <b>(d)</b> shows a stable appearance of the breast. <b>(e, f)</b> During the ensuing diagnostic evaluation, the technologist first obtained a spot compression view with the large square paddle <b>(e)</b>, which did not show the spiculated margins indicative of malignancy as clearly as did the compression view obtained with the small round paddle <b>(f)</b>, which focused more compressive force over the location of the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig12e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig12f.jpeg" height="819" width="710" aria-labelledby="fig12f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12f</span> Small invasive ductal cancer. <b>(a, b)</b> Comparison of CC views obtained in 2012 <b>(a)</b> and 2010 <b>(b)</b> shows a one-view asymmetry (arrow in <b>a</b>) with questionable architectural distortion. <b>(c, d)</b> Comparison of MLO views acquired in 2012 <b>(c)</b> and 2010 <b>(d)</b> shows a stable appearance of the breast. <b>(e, f)</b> During the ensuing diagnostic evaluation, the technologist first obtained a spot compression view with the large square paddle <b>(e)</b>, which did not show the spiculated margins indicative of malignancy as clearly as did the compression view obtained with the small round paddle <b>(f)</b>, which focused more compressive force over the location of the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig12f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig13a.jpeg" height="838" width="421" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Changing the obliquity of the diagnostic mammographic view may improve the depiction of small cancers with minimal desmoplastic reaction that appear effaced by spot compression. <b>(a)</b> MLO view shows a small low-density asymmetry with a questionable architectural distortion (arrow) in the posterior portion of the breast. <b>(b)</b> MLO spot compression view obtained at callback shows apparent effacement of the asymmetry, with no architectural distortion. Although our institution routinely obtains ML views during callback evaluations, for an unknown reason no ML view was acquired in this case. Findings at breast US were negative, and the patient resumed annual screening. <b>(c, d)</b> MLO view obtained the following year showed a more obvious abnormality (arrow in <b>c</b>) that persisted on the ML view <b>(d)</b>. An invasive ductal cancer was diagnosed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig13b.jpeg" height="838" width="538" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Changing the obliquity of the diagnostic mammographic view may improve the depiction of small cancers with minimal desmoplastic reaction that appear effaced by spot compression. <b>(a)</b> MLO view shows a small low-density asymmetry with a questionable architectural distortion (arrow) in the posterior portion of the breast. <b>(b)</b> MLO spot compression view obtained at callback shows apparent effacement of the asymmetry, with no architectural distortion. Although our institution routinely obtains ML views during callback evaluations, for an unknown reason no ML view was acquired in this case. Findings at breast US were negative, and the patient resumed annual screening. <b>(c, d)</b> MLO view obtained the following year showed a more obvious abnormality (arrow in <b>c</b>) that persisted on the ML view <b>(d)</b>. An invasive ductal cancer was diagnosed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig13c.jpeg" height="838" width="422" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span> Changing the obliquity of the diagnostic mammographic view may improve the depiction of small cancers with minimal desmoplastic reaction that appear effaced by spot compression. <b>(a)</b> MLO view shows a small low-density asymmetry with a questionable architectural distortion (arrow) in the posterior portion of the breast. <b>(b)</b> MLO spot compression view obtained at callback shows apparent effacement of the asymmetry, with no architectural distortion. Although our institution routinely obtains ML views during callback evaluations, for an unknown reason no ML view was acquired in this case. Findings at breast US were negative, and the patient resumed annual screening. <b>(c, d)</b> MLO view obtained the following year showed a more obvious abnormality (arrow in <b>c</b>) that persisted on the ML view <b>(d)</b>. An invasive ductal cancer was diagnosed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344130066/asset/images/large/rg.344130066.fig13d.jpeg" height="838" width="444" aria-labelledby="fig13d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13d</span> Changing the obliquity of the diagnostic mammographic view may improve the depiction of small cancers with minimal desmoplastic reaction that appear effaced by spot compression. <b>(a)</b> MLO view shows a small low-density asymmetry with a questionable architectural distortion (arrow) in the posterior portion of the breast. <b>(b)</b> MLO spot compression view obtained at callback shows apparent effacement of the asymmetry, with no architectural distortion. Although our institution routinely obtains ML views during callback evaluations, for an unknown reason no ML view was acquired in this case. Findings at breast US were negative, and the patient resumed annual screening. <b>(c, d)</b> MLO view obtained the following year showed a more obvious abnormality (arrow in <b>c</b>) that persisted on the ML view <b>(d)</b>. An invasive ductal cancer was diagnosed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344130066&amp;id=fig13d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">D’Orsi CJ, Bassett LW, Berg WA, et al. Mammography. In: <em>Breast Imaging Reporting and Data System (BI-RADS)</em>. 4th ed. Reston, Va: American College of Radiology, 2003.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Mammography&amp;author=CJ+D%E2%80%99Orsi&amp;author=LW+Bassett&amp;author=WA+Berg&amp;publication_year=2003">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Sickles EA. Mammographic features of 300 consecutive nonpalpable breast cancers. <em>AJR Am J Roentgenol</em> 1986;146(4):661–663.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.2214/ajr.146.4.661">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/3485337/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Mammographic+features+of+300+consecutive+nonpalpable+breast+cancers&amp;author=EA+Sickles&amp;publication_year=1986&amp;journal=AJR+Am+J+Roentgenol&amp;pages=661-663&amp;doi=10.2214%2Fajr.146.4.661&amp;pmid=3485337">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Leung JWT, Sickles EA. Developing asymmetry identified on mammography: correlation with imaging outcome and pathologic findings. <em>AJR Am J Roentgenol</em> 2007;188(3):667–675.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref